                            <comment id="12805628" author="tdunning" created="Wed, 27 Jan 2010 19:46:22 +0000"  >
&lt;p&gt;This code looks like it uses Math.max to aggregate values.  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That seems fine.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12805634" author="jake.mannix" created="Wed, 27 Jan 2010 20:09:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Math.max is fine, and if we&apos;re going to follow the thinking of not going with large absolute value, that&apos;s ok.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;But the Double.MIN_VALUE is wrong, because new DenseVector().maxValue() should return 0, not Math.MIN_VALUE, right?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12805636" author="tdunning" created="Wed, 27 Jan 2010 20:12:59 +0000"  >
&lt;p&gt;I don&apos;t understand your point.  If there are any values at all in the dense vector, then it won&apos;t return MIN_VALUE.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On the other hand, for a sparse vector, there should be a check to return 0 if the dimension of the vector is &amp;gt;0 and there were no non-zero elements.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;What to return in the case of a 0-dimensional vector is not something I would worry about. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12805645" author="jake.mannix" created="Wed, 27 Jan 2010 20:42:49 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;0 is less than MIN_VALUE.  You&apos;re thinking of NEGATIVE_INFINITY, perhaps?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12805653" author="tdunning" created="Wed, 27 Jan 2010 21:12:11 +0000"  >
&lt;p&gt;Thank you.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Yes.  That was my thought.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
